AUDIO: 'the trace. We can see the tool call that actually happened, and we can see the state changes. Plus, here\'s the recording, which I wanted in the first place. And that is what I want as a dev,'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not just the bot worked. I want to know why it worked, when it fails, I want evidence of this actually happening. So, what is Dogora? Dogora appears to give us three different things out of all'

[03:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this. We get a voice agent, a visual workflow builder, and the platform layer you usually have to build yourself. The voice engine is the part that connects the caller, the phone provider, speech'

[03:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to text, the LLM, and text-to-speech. That is what makes the call actually happen. The workflow builder is where you design the logic of this whole system. So, instead of hard-coding every prompt, branch, API call, and transfer,'

[04:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can map out the flow visually. So, huge win here. I like these kind of maps. Ask this question, wait for the answer. That\'s kind of what we\'re mapping out here. I can call this API, branch here, transfer there. That'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of logic should be easy to change. Then to all this, there\'s the platform layer. Testing, tracing, recordings, analytics. That is the boring stuff every Series Voice project eventually needs. With all this, you can bring your'

[04:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'own providers, your own LLM, and your own TTS. Because Dogora is open source, you can inspect the code, change how it works, and self-host it. As of this recording, GitHub stars are low. So, this is a super new find that I found,'

[04:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but it\'s honestly a rather cool one. Now, let\'s compare Dogora to other things we already have out here. You have three main ways to build voice agents. First is hosted platforms. Vapi, Bland, Retell. These are good when you'

[04:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want to move fast and you don\'t want to run infrastructure. You get clean dashboards, APIs, transcript, testing tools. All that\'s really useful, but you start to lose control right there. If the platform changes pricings, you deal'

